description.narrative: Insatsen är en del av ett strategiskt partnerskap som sträcker sig mellan 2021 och 2025 mellan Oxfam och Sidas humanitära enhet. Insatsen för 2023 uppgår till 103 200 000 SEK och fördelas till projekt och program i 5 kriser, ger Oxfam möjlighet att söka om stöd genom Sidas Rapid Response Mechanism samt tre metod och kapacitetsstöd.Målet med insatsen är att skyndsamt kunna nå människor med humanitärt stöd i akuta kriser samt att bidra till att stärka kapaciteten i det humanitära systemet. Samtliga föreslagna insatser vägleds av Oxfams kärnmandat, vilket är att arbeta med samhällen innan, under och efter kriser för att bygga upp deras motståndskraft, rädda liv och tillsammans angripa orsakerna till konflikt och andra katastrofer.Jämställdhets perspektivet genomsyrar Oxfams insatser och organisationen deltar aktivt i det globala påverkansarbetet i jämställdhetsfrågor. Jämställdhetsaspekter beaktas vid utformning, genomförande och utvärdering av projekt.Oxfam är en global hjälporganisation som arbetar med människor mot fattigdom över hela världen. Oxfam:s vision är en rättvis värld utan fattigdom, där alla värderas och behandlas lika, har samma rättigheter och kan påverka sin egen framtid. Oxfam arbetar på flera nivåer, genom livräddande katastrofinsatser, långsiktiga projekt som ger människor möjlighet att lyfta sig ur fattigdom och politisk påverkan lindrar vi de akuta symptomen. Oxfam GB är ett av 20 medlemmar som utgör konfederationen Oxfam International.

The contribution for 2023 includes humanitarian support to Oxfam's projects and programmes in five crises, Oxfam's projects applied through Sida's rapid response mechanism (RRM) and for method and capacity support.
The contribution is the third year of a strategic partnership that extends between 2021 and 2025 between Oxfam and Sida's Humanitarian Unit. The aim of the contribution is to reach people affected by crisis with humanitarian assistance and protection and to contribute to strengthening the capacity of the humanitarian system. All proposed efforts are guided by Oxfam's core mandate, which is to work with communities before, during and after crises to build their resilience, save lives and tackle the causes of conflict and other disasters.
Oxfam’s strong programming capacities is on gender and the organisation actively participates in global advocacy on gender issues. Oxfam's contributions have demonstrated strong gender sensitivity in its programming and participation of women throughout program cycles. Gender aspects are taken into account when designing, implementing and evaluating projects.
Oxfam is a global movement of people who are fighting inequality to end poverty and injustice. Oxfam GB is one of 20 affiliates that make up the confederation Oxfam International.

This contribution is aimed at supporting Oxfam in selected humanitarian crisis where Oxfam will implement specific projects and where the organisation has a clear added value to provide humanitarian assistance and protection to crisis affected populations.In 2020 Oxfam launched its new Global Strategic Framework 2020-2030. It sets out the overall direction that Oxfam will take in the years to 2030. According to Oxfam, implementation of the framework will be supported by global horizon plans that will set out specific objectives, systemic interventions, and actions. These plans will serve as a roadmaps for measuring progress towards Oxfam's collective ambition. A combination of six approaches is presented in the framework and will constitute Oxfam's overarching theory of change. These include:A feminist approach- To end all forms of discrimination, injustices and violations of rights suffered by women and gender non-conforming peoplePeople power Amplify the voices and actions of people that experience poverty and injustice and work with those who fight for their causesThinking globally and acting locally- Build a coalition within and between regions and from the local to the globalEnhanced humanitarian action- remain committed to delivering life-saving assistance and protection in times of conflict and disasterDigital rights and space- to engage with and leverage the power and influence of digital technologySystematic change Mobilize to transform the systems that perpetuate poverty and injustice.The strategy also outlines Oxfams approach to enhance its humanitarian actions which involves 1) deliveing life-saving support and assistance to communities affected by conflict and disaster, including people on the move; 2) transforming the systems that contribute to fragility and humanitarian crises;3) helping people and communities develop core competencies to strengthen their resilience; 4) continue to reorient the humanitarian system towards local leadership, and; 5) expanding opportunities for those impacted by protracted conflict and recurring crises to lead on sustainable solutions.At the operational level the global strategic framework reaffirms Oxfams commitment to humanitarian assistance in the technical areas of WASH, Economic Inclusion, Cash and social protection based approaches, Gender, Community based protection and safe programming, and finally advocacy work to complement programmes in particular on women in conflict.In all the technical areas there are four pillars that will inform the humanitarian approach including 1) Community Engagement; 2) Safe Programming; 3) Partnership and Leadership, 4) Feminist approach. Oxfam has developed Horizon Plan for humanitarian action, which give practical and pragmatic guidance on expectations for Oxfam countries on its humanitarian ambition, how it is changing in approach and alignment of appropriate support. Sida's Humanitarian Assistance to Oxfam GB 2023Oxfams broad global presence at national and regional level means that existing officesand personnel on the ground can immediately respond to rapid onset crises. In addition,Oxfam has a team of humanitarian support personnel in all sectors that are on stand-byto be deployed to support the upscale of a humanitarian response.Sida considers Oxfam GB to be a partner that through its humanitarian interventionsand own Strategic Framework makes a significant contribution in meeting the objectivesof the Strategy for Swedens humanitarian aid provided through the SwedishInternational Development Cooperation Agency (Sida) 2021-2025.Sida's Humanitarian Unit has prioritized funding allocations to Oxfam, as for others, onthe basis of the evidence of the most severe humanitarian needs and of the ability of itsstrategic partners to address them efficiently, aligned with the Humanitarian ResponsePlans (HRP) and Refugee Response Plans (RRP), coordinated by the UN and the ICRCoperational appeals. OCHA's Global Humanitarian Overview 2023 sets another recordfor humanitarian relief requirements, with 339 million people in need of assistance in 69countries, an increase of 65 million people compared to the same time last year. Theestimated cost of the global humanitarian response going into 2023 is US$51.5 billion, a25 per cent increase compared to the beginning of 2022. In 2023, Sida humanitarianunit will be prioritizing 30 crises worldwide and Oxfam has been selected as one of thebest placed actors in five crises.For 2023, the following support is proposed for Oxfam:- Country-based Projects/Programmes in Algeria, CAR, Colombia, Yemen and Chad in linewith Humanitarian Response Plans or Refugee Response Plans 46 MSEK- Rapid Response Mechanism 45 MSEK- Method Development and Capacity-Building 10,2 MSEK- Programme management support 2 MSEKThis means that the total initial contribution to Oxfam GB in 2023 amounts to 103,2MSEK.Sida proposes multi-year funding for the Projects/Programmes in Chad, CAR and Algeriaas well as two Method Development and Capacity-Building projects between 2023 and 2025 at a total of 65 MSEK, this includes 37 MSEK in 2024 and 28 MSEK in 2025.I. Country-based Projects and Programmes ( (2023: 46 MSEK, 2024: 28 MSEK, 2025: 28MSEK)a. Annual Country-based Projects/ProgrammesColombia (7 MSEK) (Project)Oxfams objective is to increase the protection of migrant women and their families fromVenezuela and host communities through direct humanitarian assistance in Arauca. Oneof Oxfams comparative advantages is their way of working together with a localorganisation (Apovar) with a specific focus on vulnerability and lack of protection,especially for migrant women and host communities.Yemen (10 MSEK) (PBA)Oxfam is present in seven governorates in Yemen, focusing on FSL through multipurposecash assistance, providing WASH through water trucking and water qualityimprovement, protection through strengthening structures, facilitating access to servicesand providing legal support. Oxfams rapid response capacity is a strong reason forcontinued Sida support. Oxfam will apply a one year PBA in Yemen.b. Multi-year Country-based Projects/ProgrammesAlgeria (10 10 10 MSEK) (PBA)Refugees from Western Sahara have been living in 5 refugee camps in Tindouf since1975. In this context 95% of the refugee population depend on humanitarian aid. Sidahas identified Oxfam as key actor in critical response sectors including: WASH,Protection and Food Security and Livelihoods. Given the protracted crisis and slightlydeteriorating situations year-on-year, Sida has decided to support Oxfam Algeria withmulti-year programme based support (2023-2025).CAR (8 8 8 MSEK) (PBA)Oxfam is improving living conditions, means of production and access to WASH servicesand strengthening mechanisms to protect 76,000 displaced, returnee and hostcommunities (51% female), including GBV, in the target areas of Bria (Haute Kotto) andBatangafo (Ouham), through services, cash and in kind modalities. Oxfam will begranted multi-year programme based support (2023-2025).Chad (11 10 10 MSEK) (Project with the aim to transition to PBA in 2024)Oxfam is active in hard-to-reach areas in the Lake-region and implements protection,WASH and livelihoods activities. Oxfam targets both displaced persons and hostcommunities and specifically includes disabled persons and elderly in their interventions.Oxfam has also continued to deliver good results. Oxfam is proposed for a multi-yearproject which will be evaluated in 2023 and possibly converted to a PBA in 2024.The disbursement of the support to the country contexts for 2024 and 2025 á 56 MSEKis conditioned on the receipt of an updated workplan and budget and subject toparliamentary appropriation of funds.II. Rapid Response Mechanism (45 MSEK)Part of the annual humanitarian budget is set aside for sudden humanitarian crises anddeteriorations of major ongoing crises. For these situations Sida has an RRM withpartner organisations that makes it possible to fund lifesaving responses worldwide within24 hours.Oxfam prioritises RRM applications in hard-to-reach areas, areas with increased needsand forgotten crisis with limited international visibility. The RRM complements OxfamsCatastrophe Fund Mechanism (CAT Fund) and public appeals.Sida assesses that Oxfam has a relevant and strategic approach to the RRM and is well-placed in order to respond quickly to sudden onset crises through the RRM. ThereforeSida will increase the allocation of RRM funding by 10 MSEK to Oxfam in 2023. In 2023, 45 MSEK will be added to the Agreement with Oxfam GB to support the organisation through the modality of RRM support.III. Method- and capacity-building support (2023: 10,2 MSEK, 2024: 9 MSEK)CaLP (5 5 MSEK)Sida will in 2023 continue its support to the Cash Learning Partnership (CaLP), anetwork based on learning, knowledge sharing, networking and coordination around theappropriate and timely use of cash transfer programming (CTP) in humanitarianresponse. As CaLP is not a legal body and is hosted by the Humanitarian Department ofOxfam House, it was decided to include the support to CaLP in the Agreement betweenOxfam GB and Sida. In 2022, Sida proposed to provide multi-year support to CaLPbetween 2022-2024 with 5 MSEK per year. In 2023, Sida will continue to support CaLPwith 5 MSEK.Sida funding will support the delivery of all five strategic focus areas of the CaLP strategyfor 2020-2025.The disbursement of the support to CaLP for 2024 á 5 MSEK is conditioned on thereceipt of an updated workplan and budget and subject to parliamentary appropriationof funds.WASH Tweaks (1,2 MSEK)In 2023, Sida will support Oxfam GBs method and capacity building project calledWASH Tweaks with 1,2 MSEK and will be the final year of the multi-year supportagreed on in 2022.Research conducted in the WASH, protection and gender sectors highlights that up to40% of women do not use communal toilets in emergencies because of concerns around gender-based violence, privacy, harassment, abuse and other protection concerns.WASH Tweaks seeks to systematically increase awareness of and capacity for improvedconsultation, action on feedback, and dialogue with affected populations on the designand implementation of WASH facilities in the global WASH sector.The project will aim to increase the use of water and sanitation facilities in emergenciesthrough improved consultation brought about by a sector-wide change and will be jointlyimplemented between Oxfam and the London School of Hygiene and TropicalMedicine. The project will be implemented globally including a research study inEthiopia or Bangladesh and implementation of the WASH Tweaks approach will berolled out to a minimum of 10 countries which have large scale humanitarian WASHprogrammes and are identified by the Global WASH Cluster as high priority countries.Depending on funds available and feasibility, these countries may include Ethiopia,Bangladesh, Burkina Faso, CAR, the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), Iraq,Myanmar, Chad, South Sudan, Syria and Yemen.Frontline Community Protection (4 4 MSEK)In 2023, Sida proposes to provide multi-year support to Oxfam GB's method andcapacity-building project called Frontline Community Protection between 2023-2025with 4 MSEK per year.This project will build humanitarian capacity in three key areas: participatory feministMEAL for protection; protection advocacy; and implementing community-led protectionwork. By improving capacity, technical skills and expertise in these three areas, thisproject will contribute towards a more inclusive, coordinated and collaborativehumanitarian system that is more effective in reducing protection risks to populationsaffected by conflict and crises.The project will be implemented globally under Oxfam's Global Humanitarian Teamworking in coordination with the Global Protection Cluster and two thematic task teamson Protection Advocacy and Community-led Protection. The project will also work instrategic partnerships with up to four national NGOs with direct funding and mentorshipto support leadership functions and greater national representation in thematicprotection task teams.The disbursement of the support to the Frontline Community Protection project for2024 á 4 MSEK is conditioned on the receipt of an updated workplan and budget andsubject to parliamentary appropriation of funds.IV. description.narrative: During 2021-2022, Oxfam implemented a total of 12 projects in 10 countries includingCentral African Republic (CAR), Chad, Algeria, Colombia, Ethiopia, Kenya, Somalia,Palestine (Occupied Palestinian Territories (OPT)) and Yemen. The interventions werewithin the following sectors WASH, EFSVL, Protection and Gender. Of these, sevenprojects were Rapid Response Mechanism (RRM) projects, four were one year projectsand two were method and capacity project on improved quality and capacity inIntegrated Food Security Phase Classification (IPC) Acute Food Insecurity analysesimplemented in CAR and Zimbabwe and Cash Learning Partnership (CaLP). The HPAreached a total of 934,354 women, men, girls and boys with humanitarian assistance ofwhich approximately 51% were women and girls.Examples of results achieved through the HPA 2021/22 include:Under the Annual Project mechanism, Oxfam and its local humanitarian partnersreached a total of 224,971 crisis-affected people, of which 51.4% were women and girls,with life-saving assistance in emergency WASH, FSL, Protection and Gendermainstreaming. Protection activities reached 20% of the total number of crisis-affectedpeople reached. All four annual projects were in forgotten crises as per DG ECHOsdefinition.Oxfam implemented seven RRM projects in a total of six countries reaching 709,383crisis-affected women, men, girls and boys, of which 50.6% were women and girls.Nearly half of the RRM projects responded to natural disasters, and more preciselydrought. The remaining half of the RRM projects were dedicated to conflict responsesand political crises. Four out of the seven RRM projects were in sudden onset crises, theremaining three RRM interventions were in slow-onset climate-related crises. Three ofthe RRM projects (CAR and the two drought RRMs in Somalia) helped further scale-uppre-existing responses in forgotten crises as per ECHOs Forgotten Crisis Assessment for 2021. Of the total number reached through RRM projects, 13,228 crisis-affected peoplewere reached with stand-alone Protection assistance. However, Sida notes that Oxfamensured that Protection and Gender mainstreaming was cross-cutting in all WASH andFSL activities (which also included the majority of people reached through the RRMs).Key highlights of the 2021/22 programme period included Oxfams pre-existing localhumanitarian partnerships, community engagement and integrated and cross-cuttingresponses (including integrated WASH, FSL, Gender, Protection). More than half of allHPA projects were delivered together with local humanitarian partners who utilised29.2% of the programme spend. In for example Colombia, an RRM project in Somaliaand the RRM project in OPT, the implementing partners were in charge of more than70% of the project budget. Community engagement was central in a majority of projectswhere affected populations have participated in defining context analyses, adaptations toprogramming, outreach, capacity building, coordination and advocacy. Throughout theprogramme period, Oxfam showed many examples of their work in advocacy on forexample unrestricted humanitarian access, protection, respect for human rights, genderand localisation of aid.Oxfam reported a clear determination to reach people in hard-to-reach areas throughoutthe implementation period 2021/22. Out of ten country contexts where the HPA wasactive in 2021/22, Ethiopia had extreme access constraints, five contexts (Yemen, CAR,Colombia, OPT and Somalia) experienced very high access constraints and two (Chadand Kenya) were ranked as high access constraints. Unrestricted humanitarian access isone of Oxfams important advocacy agendas and examples of advocacy and adaptationsin projects in other to reach people in acute crisis situations and hard-to-reach areas wasevident in Oxfams annual report for 2021/22. For example, in Ethiopia, Oxfam's earlyefforts in advocacy on humanitarian access in December 2020 paved the way for on-the ground programming in April 2021.Community-based protection is a key feature in many of Oxfam's projects, such as inCAR and Yemen. The community-based protection programmes play a significant rolein addressing tension and conflict in their communities and influencing social norms aswell as influencing local authorities and decision-makers. In Yemen for example, theproject developed 12 community-based protection networks who assessed protectionneeds and risks, identified, referred and supported individuals with protection needs anddisseminated information on protection services. In CAR, almost 100% of all protectioncases referred to community protection structures received a positive solution.Furthermore, 87% of identified and referred gender-based violence (GBV) survivors weremore economically and socially independent due to income generating activity supportand education on their rights. In 2021, Oxfam also reviewed two pilots of using groupcash grants to support communities self-protection efforts in CAR and Yemen. Overallthe pilots have been greatly appreciated by all stakeholders, allowing communities to bepart of decision-making processes from the beginning and allowing more space forleadership among the community which is important in Oxfams shift to community-led protection work. In September 2021, Oxfam and partner organisations also developedand published a Resource Pack on Community-Based Protection.The method and capacity project on IPC analyses initiated work on gender within IPCanalyses, creating opportunities to engage and influence key stakeholders and launchingthe first gender-sensitive survey through work in CAR. Gender will now be included inthe next IPC Global Support Programme.At the global level, evidence reviewed for the 2021 meta-analysis highlights that Oxfammeets both internal and external quality standards in implementation. Oxfam continuesto operate in complex contexts, responding in a timely manner and is making progress ineach of its four pillars of Oxfams Humanitarian Approach Feminist Approach, LocalHumanitarian Leadership, Community Engagement and Safe Programming. Oxfam hasalso seen a significant increase in cash and voucher assistance (up by 35% compared to2020/21).

description.narrative: FAOs Global Goals are:1. Eradication of hunger, food insecurity and malnutrition, progressively ensuring a world in which people at all times have sufficient safe and nutritious food that meets their dietary needs and food preferences for an active and healthy life;2. Elimination of poverty and the driving forward of economic and social progress for all, with increased food production, enhanced rural development and sustainable livelihoods;3. Sustainable management and utilization of natural resources, including land, water, air, climate and genetic resources for the benefit of present and future generations.Based on the global goals, FAO has formulated five strategic objectives:1. Contribute to the eradication of hunger, food insecurity and malnutrition2. Make agriculture, forestry and fisheries more productive and sustainable3. Reduce rural poverty4. Enable more inclusive and efficient agricultural and food systems5. Increase the resilience of livelihoods to threats and crisesThe Strategic Framework also includes a sixth, broad objective on technical quality, knowledge and services (including cross-cutting themes) that is designed to cover FAOs internal capability to deliver its strategic objectives. The objectives are in alignment with FAOs commitment to working in partnerships.In humanitarian crises, FAOs main components are:To help people to anticipate and prepare for crises; To respond fast to crises; To seek to reduce risks and address vulnerabilities.The humanitarian operations are usually related to the 5th strategic objective which has the four following organizational outcomes (OO):OO1 - countries and regions have legal, policy and institutional systems and regulatory frameworks for disaster and crisis risk management for agriculture, food and nutrition;OO2 - countries and regions deliver regular information and trigger timely actions against potential, known and emerging threats to agriculture, food, and nutrition;OO3 - countries apply prevention and impact mitigation measures that reduce risks for agriculture, food and nutrition;OO4 - countries and regions affected by disasters and crises with impact on agriculture, food and nutrition are prepared for, and manage effective responses.At the next level in the FAO Strategic Framework, there are a number of outputs pertinent to humanitarian action, such as:Output 4.1: Humanitarian action effectively protect lives and livelihoods of farmers, herders, Fishers, forest- and tree-dependent communities and marginal groups in times of crises.Output 3.1: Strategies and related interventions improve the resilience of livelihoods systems at risk through prevention and mitigation efforts that minimize the potential impacts of disasters and crises on agriculture food and nutrition at national, subnational and community levels.Output 2.2: Improved capacities of countries and communities to identify monitor and evaluate risks; conduct needs assessment and response analysis; and act on impending threats to agriculture, nutrition, food security and food safety (and related public health issues).Output 3.3: Conflict-sensitive programmes on agriculture, food and nutrition reduce the risks of localized conflicts relating to access to grazing, forest and farming lands, fishing grounds, water, trees and other natural resources.

Insatsen syftar till att möjliggöra för FAO att svara upp mot humanitära behov genom att skydda och återställa försörjningsmöjligheter inom jordbruk och boskap. FAO kommer att stärka tryggad livsmedelsförsörjning för de mest utsatta som drabbats av konflikter, klimatförändringar och naturkatastrofer. Genom detta stöd kommer FAO att fokusera på faserna 3-5 i enlighet med IPC-skalan, dvs. (3) kris, (4) nödsituation och (5) svält/katastrof. FAO:s nya strategiska ramverk 2022-2030 utgår från de globala målen. I enlighet med ramverket kommer FAO i humanitära kontexter att fokusera på jordbruk och livsmedelskriser i länder som står inför, eller riskerar att drabbas av akuta behov inom livsmedelsförsörjning. FAO har år 2023 som mål att bistå 60 miljoner människor årligen med nöd- och resiliensinsatser, och genom investeringar i föregripande åtgärder. Detta är en ambitiös ökning från målet på 35 miljoner människor år 2019. FAO:s arbete i humanitära kriser svarar väl upp mot strategin för Sidas humanitära bistånd (2021-2025). FAO:s fokus på livsmedelsförsörjning i kombination med att skydda och återställa försörjningsmöjligheter inom jordbruk anses ha positiva effekter på både akuta behov och resiliens bland människor som lever i humanitära krissituationer. FAO har också en central roll i arbetet med föregripande arbete som syftar till att minska framtida humanitära behov. FAO har en tydlig policy för jämställdhet i kriser, vilket inkluderar att man använder ett gender perspektiv i sina underlag och hur man utformar sina program. FAO anses därför vara en värdefull strategisk humanitär partner till Sida. Med Sidas stöd på 124 miljoner SEK kommer FAO under 2022 att implementera humanitärt stöd i sex kriser: Afghanistan, Madagaskar, Mali, Niger, Nigeria och Somalia. Insatsen omfattar också oallokerade medel till nya eller förvärrande humanitära kriser genom FAO:s särskilda fond för nödsituationer och återuppbyggnad (SFERA) samt ett metodstöd som syftar till att stärka länders och lokala och nationella aktörers kapacitet för att hantera humanitära insatser.

Sida’s humanitarian support to FAO enables the organisation to respond to emergencies by protecting and restoring livelihoods with a particular focus on agriculture and livestock while addressing acute food insecurity for the most vulnerable affected by conflict and climate shocks. Through this support, FAO will focus on the phases 3-5 in the Integrated Food Security Phase Classification (IPC) i.e. (3) Crisis, (4) Emergency and (5) Catastrophe/Famine. FAO's new strategic framework 2022-2030 places the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) at the centre of its operations. In terms of programme priority areas related to humanitarian interventions, FAO will focus on agriculture and food emergencies in countries facing, or at risk of acute food insecurity, by providing urgent livelihood and nutrition assistance. The strategic framework states that by 2023 FAO aims to assist 60 million people annually with emergency and resilience interventions, and through investments in anticipatory action that will reduce humanitarian needs in the future. This is an ambitious increase from the 35 million target in 2019. The focus on both acute food security and livelihoods with positive spill-over effects on household and community resilience in combination with FAO’s leading technical expertise in agriculture and its focus on Anticipatory Action. description.narrative: Action Against Hunger (AAH) is a global humanitarian organisation that takes action against the causes and effects of hunger and malnutrition. AAH international network (AAH-IN) is composed of AAH entities from France, (Sida agreement partner), AAH India, AAH United Kingdom, AAH Spain, AAH USA and AAH Canada. Each of these members are separate legal entities, but share a common charter of principles, strategy and areas of intervention. All members of the network are committed to bringing coherence and enhancing efficiency to better serve those in need of nourishment , and to adhere to the AAH principles for which it stands. These principles are: moral and financial independence, strict political and religious neutrality, non-discrimination, free and direct access to victims, professionalism and transparency. The principles are outlined in an agreement (the International Global Protocols), which is signed by all AAH members.Through this contribution, Sida will be supporting AAH with funding which will allow for AAH to provide humanitarian assistance to affected population in more than 20 countries worldwide, such as Ethiopia, Syria, Burkina Faso, South Sudan and Sudan. While the specific objective of each intervention might differ, AAH's main mandate is within the nutrition sector, with the mission to "save, improve and protect lives by eliminating hunger through the prevention, detection and treatment of undernutrition, especially during and after emergency crises caused by situations of conflict, displacement, poverty, discrimination, inequality, or natural disaster". Nutrition interventions are complemented by activities which seek to ensure that people have access to clean water, food, healthcare and protection. By being present before and after disaster strikes, AAH is committed not only to respond to emergency needs, but also to build and to strengthen the capacity and resilience of the local communities. In line with the Sida humanitarian strategy, the objective of the response is to save lives, alleviate suffering and uphold human dignity for the benefit of people in need who have been, or are at risk of becoming, affected by armed conflicts, natural disasters or other disaster emergencies.AAH's long-term planning and performance monitoring process is laid out in a five-year International Strategic Plan (ISP), which is prepared by the AAH international network. The current International Strategic Plan (ISP3) covers the period 2021-2025 and reflects AAH's priorities. To meet the overarching impact of collective and inclusive action that empowers 25 million people to overcome hunger in 2025, the key priorities to be addressed by AAH are to:1) Save lives: Lives are saved and immediate needs are met in an effective and inclusive manner in emergency contexts;2) Collectively build resilience: People and communities are better able to withstand future shocks. Mitigation of the climate crisis and of gender inequality is embedded in the fight against hunger;3) Connect and mobilize: Citizens, communities, civil society and actors at all levels are mobilized as part of a collective movement to end hunger; 4) Create and share knowledge: Best practice in the fight against hunger is developed collaboratively by a diversity of actors and shared for the empowerment of all.In 2023, Sida supports AAH's humanitarian interventions in 19 specific contexts including five new multi-year humanitarian programmes that will be implemented during 2023-2025. Sidas contribution also supports AAH's capacity to implement life-saving responses through the Rapid Response Mechanism (RRM) as well as capacity building for protection integration and humanitarian access.

description.narrative: This statement refers to the first year of the multi-year agreement for 2021-2025, covering the implementation period 1 January 2021 to 30 April 2022. The total grant to AAH from Sidas humanitarian unit in 2021 amounted to 385 700 000 SEK, distributed among 38 interventions in 29 countries. These include: - 12 Country Programmes: Burkina Faso (15 MSEK); CAR (10 MSEK); Chad (25 MSEK); Colombia (19 MSEK); Ethiopia (32 MSEK); Iraq (8.8 MSEK); Lebanon (10 MSEK); Philippines (5 MSEK); Somalia (10 MSEK); South Sudan (27 MSEK); Syria (44 MSEK); Venezuela (8 MSEK).- 10 Projects: DRC (13 MSEK); Haïti (10 MSEK); Madagascar (18 SEK); Mali (4 MSEK); Niger (8 MSEK); Nigeria (11 MSEK); Pakistan (5 MSEK); Sudan (40 MSEK); Uganda (8 MSEK); Zimbabwe (10 MSEK).- 14 Rapid Response Mechanism (RRM) Projects: Afghanistan (3 MSEK); Colombia (3 MSEK); DRC (3 MSEK); Haïti (3.3 MSEK); India (2.3 MSEK); Kenya (2 projects, in total 6 MSEK); Mozambique (3 MSEK); Myanmar (3 MSEK); Niger (2 MSEK); Nigeria (3 MSEK); Nepal (2.5 MSEK); Opts (3 MSEK); Somalia (2.8 MSEK).- 2 Method and Capacity Development Projects: Protection integration in Nutrition (4 MSEK); Program support management costs (0.9 MSEK). In terms of funding, the largest allocations were made to the following five countries: Syria, Sudan, Ethiopia, South Sudan and Chad. Country Programmes (CP), supported through the Programme-Based Approach (PBA), represented the largest proportion of the 2021 allocation at a total of 213 800 000 SEK or 55% of the grant, followed by Annual Projects representing 33% of the total allocation. The aim of AAH is to transition fully to the PBA modality in all countries by 2023. The importance of timely reporting has been a long-standing dialogue issue with Action Against Hunger (AAH) and it is therefore note-worthy that the narrative and financial reports for 2021 were delivered as per the conditions in the Agreement (2021-2025). The formatting has also improved, as the report was submitted as one consolidated file, consisting of the various interventions supported in 2021. Although the need for reducing the volume of the reporting was highlighted in the previous Statement on Reports (doc id 17/001261), the combined reports for 2021 remain voluminous at 678 pages (as compared to 672 pages in 2020). Other observations and recommendations made in the 2020 Statement on Reports include to enhance the focus on outcome level reporting, in particular for Country Programmes applying the PBA, and to clearly demonstrate the impact of integrating gender considerations into operations. Furthermore, it was recommended to where relevant combine the reports pertaining to a specific country or crisis as a way of further reducing the number of documents submitted. AGGREGATED RESULTSAt global level, the following overall results were achieved in 2021: - More than 3 million people were reached with humanitarian assistance, or which 55% female and 45% male (an increase of about 1 million as compared to the total in the previous reporting period); - More than 180,000 people received cash (same level as in 2020) for a value of 35 MSEK, and more than 25,000 peopled received vouchers (about half of what was achieved in 2020); - More than 100,000 people received food assistance (a reduction from 2020) and almost 250,000 received livelihood support (more than two-fold increase from 2020); - More than 260,000 people received nutrition support; - Around 1,2 M people were reached with improved access to health services and clean water, sanitation and hygiene (WaSH) respectively;- The amount of funding channelled to national and local responders represented close to 10% (or 18% as a proportion of direct costs), at a total of 36,518,452 SEK distributed among partners in 15 countries. Within AAHs multisectoral response, health and WaSH constituted the largest sectors with humanitarian assistance provided to 38% and 37% respectively of the total rightsholders reached in 2021. The response was primarily delivered through services (34%), followed by in-kind distributions (16%) and cash (6%).

Reprogrammed funds to address COVID-19 Reprogrammed funds to mitigate the impact of COVID-19 The mission of AAH is to save, improve and protect lives by eliminating hunger through the prevention, detection and treatment of undernutrition, especially during and after emergency crises caused by situations of conflict, displacement, poverty, discrimination, inequality, or natural disaster.
The funding to Action Against Hunger (AAH) in 202, which is encompassed in decision nr 2022-001383, is based on the Sida humanitarian allocation process that took place in late 2021 and 2022. The current decision concerns a financial contribution to AAH amounting to 411,5 MSEK.
The following modality of support is financed: 1. Country Programmes/annual projects in 20 countries – 348,5 MSEK; 2. Rapid Response Mechanism - 50 MSEK; 3. Capacity Building Support – 8 MSEK; 4. Method Support – 5 MSEK.
During 2022 the programme and project support covers the following 20 countries/crises: Burkina Faso, Central African Republic, Chad, Colombia, Democratic Republic of Congo, Ethiopia, Haiti, Iraq, Kenya, Lebanon, Madagascar, Niger, Nigeria, Somalia, Sudan, South Sudan, Syria, Uganda, Ukraine and Venezuela. Five countries have multi-year funding during the period 2022-2024, namely: Chad, Ethiopia, Somalia, South Sudan and Syria.
The project and country programmes includes support to the sectors of nutrition, protection, food security, health, livelihood, shelter, GBV and WASH.
Through their work, AAH contributes towards enabling access of disaster affected populations to essential services such as prevention and treatment of major childhood illnesses (e.g. measles, diarrhoea), improving infant and young child feeding practices, and treatment of acute malnutrition among children and mothers through the provision of supplementary and therapeutic foods. The intervention is therefore assessed to contribute to Reproductive, maternal, newborn and child health (RMNCH).
Furthermore, gender equality is a cross-cutting perspective in the interventions and is taken into consideration through: gender analysis that inform the programme/project design; interventions adopt a “do no harm” approach by e.g. targeting both displaced populations and host communities; results frameworks incorporate gender-specific indicators and disaggregated data; and monitoring of AAH’s Gender Equality Policy (approved 2021). In all contexts, complaints and response mechanisms are established through which any cases of misconduct or Sexual Exploitation, Abuse and Harassment (SEAH) are reported.
Background: AAH is a non-profit organisation, previously known as Action Contre La Faim (ACF), which is governed by the French Association Law of July 1, 1901. AAH was established in 1979 specifically to respond to humanitarian emergencies, focusing on issues of malnutrition.
AAH international network (AAH-IN) is composed of AAH entities from France, (Sida agreement partner), AAH India, AAH United Kingdom, AAH Spain, AAH USA and AAH Canada. Each of these members are separate legal entities, but share a common charter of principles, strategy and areas of intervention. All members of the network are committed to bringing coherence and enhancing efficiency to better serve those in need of nourishment , and to adhere to the AAH principles for which it stands. These principles are: moral and financial independence, strict political and religious neutrality, non-discrimination, free and direct access to victims, professionalism and transparency. The principles are outlined in an agreement (the International Global Protocols), which is signed by all AAH members.

description.narrative: This statement refers to the first year of the multi-year agreement for 2021-2025, covering the implementation period 1 January 2021 to 30 April 2022. The total grant to AAH from Sidas humanitarian unit in 2021 amounted to 385 700 000 SEK, distributed among 38 interventions in 29 countries. These include: - 12 Country Programmes: Burkina Faso (15 MSEK); CAR (10 MSEK); Chad (25 MSEK); Colombia (19 MSEK); Ethiopia (32 MSEK); Iraq (8.8 MSEK); Lebanon (10 MSEK); Philippines (5 MSEK); Somalia (10 MSEK); South Sudan (27 MSEK); Syria (44 MSEK); Venezuela (8 MSEK).- 10 Projects: DRC (13 MSEK); Haïti (10 MSEK); Madagascar (18 SEK); Mali (4 MSEK); Niger (8 MSEK); Nigeria (11 MSEK); Pakistan (5 MSEK); Sudan (40 MSEK); Uganda (8 MSEK); Zimbabwe (10 MSEK).- 14 Rapid Response Mechanism (RRM) Projects: Afghanistan (3 MSEK); Colombia (3 MSEK); DRC (3 MSEK); Haïti (3.3 MSEK); India (2.3 MSEK); Kenya (2 projects, in total 6 MSEK); Mozambique (3 MSEK); Myanmar (3 MSEK); Niger (2 MSEK); Nigeria (3 MSEK); Nepal (2.5 MSEK); Opts (3 MSEK); Somalia (2.8 MSEK).- 2 Method and Capacity Development Projects: Protection integration in Nutrition (4 MSEK); Program support management costs (0.9 MSEK). In terms of funding, the largest allocations were made to the following five countries: Syria, Sudan, Ethiopia, South Sudan and Chad. Country Programmes (CP), supported through the Programme-Based Approach (PBA), represented the largest proportion of the 2021 allocation at a total of 213 800 000 SEK or 55% of the grant, followed by Annual Projects representing 33% of the total allocation. The aim of AAH is to transition fully to the PBA modality in all countries by 2023. The importance of timely reporting has been a long-standing dialogue issue with Action Against Hunger (AAH) and it is therefore note-worthy that the narrative and financial reports for 2021 were delivered as per the conditions in the Agreement (2021-2025). The formatting has also improved, as the report was submitted as one consolidated file, consisting of the various interventions supported in 2021. Although the need for reducing the volume of the reporting was highlighted in the previous Statement on Reports (doc id 17/001261), the combined reports for 2021 remain voluminous at 678 pages (as compared to 672 pages in 2020). Other observations and recommendations made in the 2020 Statement on Reports include to enhance the focus on outcome level reporting, in particular for Country Programmes applying the PBA, and to clearly demonstrate the impact of integrating gender considerations into operations. Furthermore, it was recommended to where relevant combine the reports pertaining to a specific country or crisis as a way of further reducing the number of documents submitted. AGGREGATED RESULTSAt global level, the following overall results were achieved in 2021: - More than 3 million people were reached with humanitarian assistance, or which 55% female and 45% male (an increase of about 1 million as compared to the total in the previous reporting period); - More than 180,000 people received cash (same level as in 2020) for a value of 35 MSEK, and more than 25,000 peopled received vouchers (about half of what was achieved in 2020); - More than 100,000 people received food assistance (a reduction from 2020) and almost 250,000 received livelihood support (more than two-fold increase from 2020); - More than 260,000 people received nutrition support; - Around 1,2 M people were reached with improved access to health services and clean water, sanitation and hygiene (WaSH) respectively;- The amount of funding channelled to national and local responders represented close to 10% (or 18% as a proportion of direct costs), at a total of 36,518,452 SEK distributed among partners in 15 countries. Within AAHs multisectoral response, health and WaSH constituted the largest sectors with humanitarian assistance provided to 38% and 37% respectively of the total rightsholders reached in 2021. The response was primarily delivered through services (34%), followed by in-kind distributions (16%) and cash (6%).

Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) is Norway's largest international humanitarian organisation and widely recognized as a leading field-based displacement agency within the international humanitarian community. NRC is the INGO receiving the largest contribution from Sida's Humanitarian Unit to INGOs so far, based on experience of successful partnerships, NRC's capacities to respond at scale and its coverage of crises that Sida is prioritizing through the needs-based allocation approach. NRC receives approximately 8% of Sida's humanitarian unit's annual budget appropriation.The objectives of NRC can be summarized as follows: "To protect the rights of displaced and vulnerable people during crisis, to provide assistance meeting their immediate humanitarian needs, to prevent further displacement and to contribute to durable solutions, and to provide expertise as a strategic partner to humanitarian systems and actors." NRCs main activity is delivery of humanitarian assistance through programme activities in the field. NRC specializes in six areas of expertise, or "core competencies": shelter and settlements; livelihoods and food security; information, counselling and legal assistance (ICLA); education; camp management; and water, sanitation and hygiene promotion (WASH). Protection is lifted up as a new core competency of NRC since 2021. NRC engages closely with the affected populations to understand their needs and capacities, ensuring it tailors its assistance accordingly and involve them in the entire programme cycle, from design through implementation to evaluation. NRC advocates for respect for the rights of displaced and vulnerable people.In 2021, the NRC Board approved the Global Strategy 20222025. The strategysets out four sub-objectives for areas that NRC will continue to strengthen and further institutionalize, namely, 1. assistance to hard-to-reach populations, 2. humanitarian policy, 3. protection, and 4. durable solutions. It also points to four areas of work that will be accelerated through expanded engagement and investments: i) advocacy, ii) climate and environment, iii) collaboration with local actors, and iv) quality programming.NRCs work is divided into three pillars: humanitarian assistance, advocacy and expert deployment. Sida's Humanitarian Unit funding will continue prioritizing mainly the first pillar through funding of the humanitarian country programmes in line with HRPs and the RRPs and through the RRM funding. To some extent, Sida will support as well the second pillar of advocacy which is integrated in the humanitarian country programmes and implemented by NRC's method, thematic and capacity development projects supported by Sida. Sida will provide NRC with only a punctual support to the third pillar, through funding to CashCap which is deploying experts to the field for invigorating cash assistance working groups (17 in 2020 to 16 countries).The Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) has applied for a renewed strategic partnership with Sida during 2021-2025.The interventions tentative total budget is 4 263 200 000 Norwegian krona (NOK), that the organisation is financing with Sidas funding in a proportion of 8% approximately. Other donors, like the Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, DG ECHO, UNHCR, etc. are the largest contributors, besides a dozen of other donors in agreement with NRC. Sida provides NRC with the opportunity to allocate resources flexibly within individual country programmes (Programme-Based Approach PBA).NRC was granted funding to carry out the Humanitarian Programme for 2022 in 24 humanitarian crisis settings: Afghanistan, Cameroon, Central African Republic, Colombia, DR Congo, Ethiopia, Irak, Jordan, Kenya, Lebanon, Libya, Mali, Moçambique, Niger, Nigeria, Palestine, Somalia, Sudan, South Sudan, Syria, Uganda, Ukraina, Venezuela and Yemen. The grant includes provision of funding replenish the Rapid Response Mechanism funding instrument and four individual projects for method, capacity-building and coordination.Sida's assessment on performance and resultsAlike many other actors in the sector, NRC excels in reporting activities and outputs, but should be better in catching what changes and impacts its interventions have resulted to ultimately on assisted communities. The reporting of data and results does not provide necessarily an accurate and consolidated overview of what NRC has achieved. Sida has notified NRC that it should provide dis-aggregated data by age in targeting and reporting which is a norm.It is assumed that NRC will achieve its objectives in 2023 again, but the global stress on the current resource mobilisation system supporting humanitarian action may affect NRC as well, similarly to large humanitarian actors such as the ICRC.

Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) is Norway's largest international humanitarian organisation and widely recognized as a leading field-based displacement agency within the international humanitarian community. NRC is the INGO receiving the largest contribution from Sida's Humanitarian Unit to INGOs so far, based on experience of successful partnerships, NRC's capacities to respond at scale and its coverage of crises that Sida is prioritizing through the needs-based allocation approach. NRC receives approximately 8% of Sida's humanitarian unit's annual budget appropriation.The objectives of NRC can be summarized as follows: "To protect the rights of displaced and vulnerable people during crisis, to provide assistance meeting their immediate humanitarian needs, to prevent further displacement and to contribute to durable solutions, and to provide expertise as a strategic partner to humanitarian systems and actors." NRCs main activity is delivery of humanitarian assistance through programme activities in the field. NRC specializes in six areas of expertise, or "core competencies": shelter and settlements; livelihoods and food security; information, counselling and legal assistance (ICLA); education; camp management; and water, sanitation and hygiene promotion (WASH). Protection is lifted up as a new core competency of NRC since 2021. NRC engages closely with the affected populations to understand their needs and capacities, ensuring it tailors its assistance accordingly and involve them in the entire programme cycle, from design through implementation to evaluation. NRC advocates for respect for the rights of displaced and vulnerable people.In 2021, the NRC Board approved the Global Strategy 20222025. The strategysets out four sub-objectives for areas that NRC will continue to strengthen and further institutionalize, namely, 1. assistance to hard-to-reach populations, 2. humanitarian policy, 3. protection, and 4. durable solutions. It also points to four areas of work that will be accelerated through expanded engagement and investments: i) advocacy, ii) climate and environment, iii) collaboration with local actors, and iv) quality programming.NRCs work is divided into three pillars: humanitarian assistance, advocacy and expert deployment. Sida's Humanitarian Unit funding will continue prioritizing mainly the first pillar through funding of the humanitarian country programmes in line with HRPs and the RRPs and through the RRM funding. To some extent, Sida will support as well the second pillar of advocacy which is integrated in the humanitarian country programmes and implemented by NRC's method, thematic and capacity development projects supported by Sida. Sida will provide NRC with only a punctual support to the third pillar, through funding to CashCap which is deploying experts to the field for invigorating cash assistance working groups (17 in 2020 to 16 countries).The Norwegian Refugee Council (NRC) has applied for a renewed strategic partnership with Sida during 2021-2025.The interventions tentative total budget is 4 263 200 000 Norwegian krona (NOK), that the organisation is financing with Sidas funding in a proportion of 8% approximately. Other donors, like the Norwegian Ministry of Foreign Affairs, DG ECHO, UNHCR, etc. are the largest contributors, besides a dozen of other donors in agreement with NRC. Sida provides NRC with the opportunity to allocate resources flexibly within individual country programmes (Programme-Based Approach PBA).NRC was granted funding to carry out the Humanitarian Programme for 2022 in 24 humanitarian crisis settings: Afghanistan, Cameroon, Central African Republic, Colombia, DR Congo, Ethiopia, Irak, Jordan, Kenya, Lebanon, Libya, Mali, Moçambique, Niger, Nigeria, Palestine, Somalia, Sudan, South Sudan, Syria, Uganda, Ukraina, Venezuela and Yemen. The grant includes provision of funding replenish the Rapid Response Mechanism funding instrument and four individual projects for method, capacity-building and coordination.Sida's assessment on performance and resultsAlike many other actors in the sector, NRC excels in reporting activities and outputs, but should be better in catching what changes and impacts its interventions have resulted to ultimately on assisted communities. The reporting of data and results does not provide necessarily an accurate and consolidated overview of what NRC has achieved. Sida has notified NRC that it should provide dis-aggregated data by age in targeting and reporting which is a norm.It is assumed that NRC will achieve its objectives in 2023 again, but the global stress on the current resource mobilisation system supporting humanitarian action may affect NRC as well, similarly to large humanitarian actors such as the ICRC.

description.narrative: SRK bedöms av Sida ha god kapacitet, kompetens och förankring för att genomföra den verksamhet som SRK söker stöd för. Ett tydligt mervärde vad gäller SRK är att organisationen är del av Röda kors- och Röda halvmånerörelsen som består av ett omfattande nätverk som inkluderar ICRC, IFRC och över 190 nationella Röda kors och Röda halvmåneföreningar och 13 miljoner volontärer på plats världen över.SRK kommer att stärka nationella föreningars kapacitet att leverera en snabbt och relevant humanitär respons samt att arbeta med katastrofriskreducering. SRK kommer också att bidra till en koordinerad och effektiv rörelse som möjliggör projekt med hög kvalitet och i linje med internationella standarder.De tio specifika kontexterna som täcks av SRK:s ansökan är Niger, Sydsudan, Bangladesh, DPRK, Irak, Libanon, Palestina, Syrien, Centralamerika och Colombia/ Venezuela. Stödet gäller främst fyra sektorer: vatten och sanitet; hälsa; familjeåterförening och skydd samt katastrofriskreducering. Fokus i ansökningarna för de olika landkontexterna syftar till att bidra med tidskritiskt relevant humanitärt stöd för att rädda liv och lindra nöd, vilket är i linje med Sidas humanitära strategi. Insatserna bidrar också till ökad resiliens och värdighet genom att den nationella föreningarna, volontärer och lokala strukturer stärks för att säkra hållbarhet och kvalitet i insatserna.

The aim of the projects is to provide timely and relevant support to people in situations of acute crisis and to strengthen the resilience of people and communities in vulnerable situations to better prepare for, cope with and recover from crises. Sida's analysis is that SRC has the capacity and competence to implement the activities listed in the application. SRC's added value is the large network of over 190 national societies and over 13 million volunteers all over the world.
SRC will strengthen the capacity of the national societies to deliver a rapid and relevant humanitarian assistance and also to work on Disaster Risk Reduction. SRC also aims at supporting the National Society partners to contribute to a stronger and more effective International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement (RCRC) Movement.
The proposal covers projects in 10 contexts including: Niger, South Sudan, Bangladesh, DPRK, Iraq, Lebanon, Palestine, Syria, Northern Triangle and Venezuela/Colombia. This support is mainly covering four sectors: Water, Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH); health; Restoring Family Links (RFL) and protection; Disaster Risk Reduction (DRR). The focus is on saving lives through a relevant humanitarian assistance, in line with Sida’s humanitarian strategy 2021-2025, part of the projects also aims at increasing resilience and dignity through strengthening the national society, volunteers and local structures to ensure sustainability and quality throughout the project cycle.

The objectives of the interventions proposed by SRC for 2022 are in line with Sidas Humanitarian Strategy 2021-2025. The interventions intend to provide relevant and rapid support to people in acute crisis and to strengthen the resilience of people and communities. The annual projects are implemented in South Sudan, Bangladesh, the DPRK, Lebanon, Palestine, and Syria. The interventions focus on four sectors: water and sanitation, health, family reunification and protection as well as disaster risk reduction, and aim to contribute with time-critical humanitarian support to save lives and alleviate suffering. The projects will also contribute to increased resilience by the national societies, and sustainability will be ensured by strengthening volunteers and local structures.SRC contributes to enhance the overall capacity within the Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement to implement projects with high quality. Particular focus for 2022 is to strengthen the capacity of partners to respond to national emergencies, with focus on an environmental/climate perspective (Green Response). SRC has applied for support to a specific capacity building project that will provide effective and green WaSH support to targeted population with local means.In line with Grand Bargain's workstream to increase locally led humanitarian aid, SRC will continue to strengthen the work of volunteers through the project "Volunteering in Conflicts and Emergencies". SRC assumes that better trained and prepared volunteers will be more resilient and able to handle the various risks that they are exposed to in their work. This project is a continuation of the methods project supported in 2021, with the objective of 1) increasing the safety, well-being and resilience of volunteers; and 2) developing flexible, independent and sustainable networks and groups of volunteers who have the capacity to respond to humanitarian needs in sudden disasters but through a longer-term humanitarian effort.SRC will respond to new crises or rapidly escalating crisis by using the Rapid Response Mechanism (RRM) and funding for the IFRC's Disaster Response Emergency Fund (DREF). In terms of SRC emergency response capacity, SRC holds three WaSH ERU modules ready for deployment, supports the CCM-C (Community Case Management Cholera) Public Health ERU and is developing a IPC (Infection, Prevention, Control) Public Health ERU. A pool of trained delegates are ready to deploy to both ICRC and IFRC operations.SRC increased its support to the DREF in 2022 as well as its engagement in the fund. SRC received the double amount of funds for the DREF from Sida for 2022 compared to 2021. DREF is considered to be the fastest tool within the Movement for securing locally-led and -owned humanitarian response in the event of a disaster, and it is Sidas assessment that it is one of the most efficient funding mechanisms to enable rapid humanitarian response, including in hard to reach areas. Sida will also engage in more discussions with SRC the coming year on how we can support the Forecast Based Action (FbA) window of the DREF to enhance early action through pre-positioning, readiness and pre-agreed early action activities.With funding from Sida SRC will also continue to provide technical support to ICRC through delegates deployed to the ICRC within thematic areas where SRC has expertise and competencies. SRC delegates work mainly within WaSH, health and protection with a focus on those context where SRC has a longer-term engagement or other prioritised humanitarian contexts. ICRC has expressed that it highly values the expertise that Swedish delegates hold and their added value to the operations. The delegates are, upon their return to SRC, also able to contribute with their experience and knowledge gained from the work with the ICRC.

description.narrative:
In the early morning of Monday the 6th of February, a major earthquake of magnitude 7.8, on the Richter scale hit southern Turkey and northwestern Syria. The earthquake caused a large number of casualties and widespread destruction to infrastructure and civilian buildings in both southern Turkey and Northern Syria. Just a few hours later, in the afternoon, a second earthquake of 7.5 magnitude was recorded, whose epicenter was also in southern Turkey. In addition, dozens of aftershocks of lesser intensity followed the initial earthquake and further damage is expected in the coming days.

This major humanitarian disaster calls for immediate action. All partners have presence on the ground and can scale up their response immediately. In light of the current crisis, we initiated the Acute Crisis Mechanism. This proposal focuses on multiple sectors.

title.narrative: 2023 - MoFA-SHO Syria Earthquake - 3rd (50%)

description.narrative: On the 6th of February at close to 4:17 am, a 7.8 degrees magnitude earthquake struck southern Turkey near Syria’s northern border. The US Geological Survey said the earthquake was centered about 33 km (20 miles) from Gaziantep, a major city and provincial capital. Tremors were felt as far away as Lebanon, Greece, Palestine and the island of Cyprus. Another big earthquake was felt on the same day at around 1:24 pm local time, largely in the same affected areas.

The strategy of the IFRC response will be to contribute to support 300,000 affected people in the affected areas for a period of 11 months. Targeting will prioritize the most vulnerable groups such as separated families, female-headed households, children, people with disabilities and the elderly among other groups of special needs.

Through this Emergency Appeal, the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies (IFRC) together with the partner national societies aim to support the Syrian Arab Red Crescent Society in the response to this Syria Earthquake.
